<section xmlns="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" version="5.0" xml:lang="en" xml:id="block.GraphTheoryDirectedGraph"
         role="block">
  <title>Directed Graph in Graph Theory</title>

  <para>
    In graph theory a directed graph is a specialization of a graph, in that it only supports edges
    that are ordered pairs of vertices. These edges are named 'arrows'.
  </para>

  <para>
    A directed graph is an ordered pair
    <inlineequation>
      <mathphrase>G = (V, A)</mathphrase>
    </inlineequation>
    .
  </para>

  <para>
    Where
  </para>

  <itemizedlist>
    <listitem>
      <para>
        <inlineequation>
          <mathphrase>V</mathphrase>
        </inlineequation>
        is a set of vertices
        <inlineequation>
          <mathphrase>V = (v_1, v_2, ...)</mathphrase>
        </inlineequation>
        .
      </para>
    </listitem>
    <listitem>
      <para>
        <inlineequation>
          <mathphrase>E</mathphrase>
        </inlineequation>
        is a set or bag of arrows
        <inlineequation>
          <mathphrase>A = (a_1, a_2, ...)</mathphrase>
        </inlineequation>
        .
      </para>
    </listitem>
    <listitem>
      <para>
        An arrow
        <inlineequation>
          <mathphrase>a ∈ A</mathphrase>
        </inlineequation>
        is an ordered pair of vertices
        <inlineequation>
          <mathphrase>a = (v_i, v_j), v_i ∈ V, v_j ∈ V</mathphrase>
        </inlineequation>
        .
      </para>
    </listitem>
  </itemizedlist>
</section>
